1
00:00:29,789 --> 00:00:32,791
There was a time when
"energy" was a dirty word.

2
00:00:33,124 --> 00:00:35,418
When turning on your
lights was a hard choice.

3
00:00:36,044 --> 00:00:37,379
Cities in brownout,...

4
00:00:37,505 --> 00:00:40,924
food shortages,
cars burning fuel to run.

5
00:00:41,133 --> 00:00:42,510
But that was the past.

6
00:00:42,801 --> 00:00:46,471
Where are we now?
How do we make the world so much better?

7
00:00:46,889 --> 00:00:48,640
Make deserts bloom!

8
00:00:49,892 --> 00:00:53,354
Right now, we are the largest
producer of fusion energy in the world.

9
00:00:53,980 --> 00:00:56,149
The energy of the sun,
trapped in rock,

10
00:00:56,274 --> 00:00:58,860
harvested by machine from
the far side of the moon.

11
00:01:00,445 --> 00:01:03,448
Today, we deliver enough
clean-burning helium-3...

12
00:01:03,573 --> 00:01:07,202
to supply the energy needs
of nearly 70% of the planet.

13
00:01:08,579 --> 00:01:11,498
Who would have thought that all
energy we ever needed

14
00:01:11,790 --> 00:01:13,584
is right above our heads?

15
00:01:15,669 --> 00:01:17,212
The power of the moon...

16
00:01:17,838 --> 00:01:20,132
the power of our future.

17
00:02:34,292 --> 00:02:36,461
Rock and roll!
08:32, Pacific Time.

18
00:02:36,670 --> 00:02:38,546
All harvesters running smoothly.

19
00:02:38,755 --> 00:02:40,423
Readouts are as follows:

20
00:02:40,549 --> 00:02:43,260
Matthew...14.6 miles.

21
00:02:43,551 --> 00:02:45,762
Mark...16.8 miles.

22
00:02:46,262 --> 00:02:47,639
I don't—

23
00:02:55,981 --> 00:02:58,567
Hey, Gerty? Gerty?
Wake up!

24
00:02:59,193 --> 00:03:00,652
Good morning, Sam!

25
00:03:01,194 --> 00:03:02,655
We have got a live one on Mark!

26
00:03:02,863 --> 00:03:04,531
I'm going to go out
now and rope her in.

27
00:03:04,824 --> 00:03:05,992
OK, Sam.

28
00:04:02,508 --> 00:04:03,551
I want chocolate.

29
00:04:03,968 --> 00:04:05,428
I think you're sweet enough.

30
00:04:05,636 --> 00:04:06,888
You don't need chocolate.

31
00:04:17,816 --> 00:04:20,110
[Computer]:
Searching for long-range comms.

32
00:04:24,489 --> 00:04:26,783
Searching for long-range comms.

33
00:04:30,453 --> 00:04:33,248
Signal failure on long-range comms.

34
00:05:44,989 --> 00:05:46,867
Sam Bell, reporting to Central...

35
00:05:47,409 --> 00:05:49,911
10:14, Pacific Time.

36
00:05:51,163 --> 00:05:54,374
I have a full container full of helium-3,
ready to roll.

37
00:05:54,791 --> 00:05:57,294
By the time this message reaches you,
it should be in transit.

38
00:05:57,419 --> 00:05:59,505
Otherwise, everything running smoothly...

39
00:06:01,048 --> 00:06:02,299
How are things down there?

40
00:06:04,384 --> 00:06:05,844
You guys been having any...

41
00:06:07,096 --> 00:06:08,889
good parties or anything?

42
00:06:09,181 --> 00:06:10,975
Oh, thanks for the...(stumbles)

43
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:14,812
for the football feed!
It almost felt live.

44
00:06:15,854 --> 00:06:17,022
Almost!

45
00:06:18,691 --> 00:06:20,860
Three years is a long haul.

46
00:06:21,902 --> 00:06:25,156
You know—
It's way, way, way, way, way too long!

47
00:06:25,865 --> 00:06:27,325
I'm talking to myself...

48
00:06:27,742 --> 00:06:29,118
on a regular basis!

49
00:06:29,327 --> 00:06:30,453
So...

50
00:06:32,247 --> 00:06:34,207
Time to go home,
you know what I mean?

51
00:06:35,667 --> 00:06:37,669
That's it,
over and out!

52
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:40,255
Rock and roll,
God bless America!

53
00:06:58,607 --> 00:07:00,692
I can do that for you, Sam.

54
00:07:04,655 --> 00:07:06,866
God damn it!
I said I got it!

55
00:07:07,908 --> 00:07:09,577
Why don't you listen to me?

56
00:07:17,919 --> 00:07:19,587
Package ready for launch.

57
00:07:43,237 --> 00:07:44,906
Sam, is everything OK?

58
00:07:48,868 --> 00:07:50,537
- Sam?
- What?

59
00:07:51,496 --> 00:07:53,372
You don't seem like yourself today.

60
00:07:53,581 --> 00:07:56,501
- Is something wrong?
- No. Can you turn that off, please?

61
00:07:57,127 --> 00:07:58,461
Jesus Christ!

62
00:08:01,381 --> 00:08:03,884
Sam, it might help you
to talk about it.

63
00:08:07,012 --> 00:08:08,805
Gerty, have you heard anything new
about anyone fixing Lunar-Sat?

64
00:08:08,888 --> 00:08:10,265
the setting of monthly satellite dishes?

65
00:08:10,556 --> 00:08:11,558
No, Sam.

66
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,560
From what I understand,
it is fairly low...

67
00:08:13,602 --> 00:08:15,979
on the company's priority list right now.

68
00:08:16,104 --> 00:08:17,564
You tell them to sort that out.

69
00:08:17,648 --> 00:08:20,066
You know what I'm talking about?
That's not—

70
00:08:20,776 --> 00:08:22,235
I've only got two weeks!

71
00:08:22,444 --> 00:08:25,364
But it's not fair for
whoever's coming up here next.

72
00:08:25,697 --> 00:08:29,118
I will, Sam. Do you want me
to finish cutting your hair later?

73
00:08:29,327 --> 00:08:31,203
No, come on;
let's finish this.

74
00:08:34,957 --> 00:08:36,334
Got one of those headaches...

75
00:08:37,043 --> 00:08:38,628
Can you—can you give me
something for it?

76
00:08:59,775 --> 00:09:01,651
[Gerty]: Message received
from your wife, Sam...

77
00:09:01,860 --> 00:09:03,528
via Jupiter link.

78
00:09:06,031 --> 00:09:06,865
Fuck!

79
00:09:14,081 --> 00:09:16,166
Hi, Sam!
It's me.

80
00:09:19,086 --> 00:09:20,755
I got your last message.

81
00:09:21,172 --> 00:09:23,549
It was really good
to hear your voice.

82
00:09:23,966 --> 00:09:25,551
I miss you, too!

83
00:09:26,802 --> 00:09:28,761
I know you're really lonely up there...

84
00:09:29,596 --> 00:09:32,516
But I think...
In a lot of ways....

85
00:09:33,475 --> 00:09:35,227
it's been really good for you.

86
00:09:35,977 --> 00:09:37,229
For both of us.

87
00:09:38,564 --> 00:09:40,982
God, I hope you do not mind me saying that.

88
00:09:44,403 --> 00:09:45,863
I'm proud of you!

89
00:09:47,532 --> 00:09:49,200
Someone has got something to say.

90
00:09:52,328 --> 00:09:53,913
What did you want to say to daddy, baby?

91
00:09:55,874 --> 00:09:57,666
Say "astronaut".

92
00:09:58,292 --> 00:10:00,253
Astronaut.
(Sam chuckles)

93
00:10:01,003 --> 00:10:02,338
He is an astronaut!

94
00:10:02,672 --> 00:10:06,092
(whispering) Say daddy's an astronaut.
Say it really loud.

95
00:10:06,426 --> 00:10:08,595
Daddy's an astronaut.

96
00:10:09,345 --> 00:10:11,014
Clever girl!
Wave!

97
00:10:11,306 --> 00:10:13,308
Give daddy a wave!

98
00:10:14,643 --> 00:10:16,645
Kathy, could you—

99
00:10:18,814 --> 00:10:21,024
I can't believe you're
going to be home soon.

100
00:10:22,693 --> 00:10:24,653
It's her birthday next month...

101
00:10:25,196 --> 00:10:27,990
And I was thinking about
maybe a playhouse for the garden.

102
00:10:28,198 --> 00:10:30,283
- Gerty!
- We could work at it together.

103
00:10:31,451 --> 00:10:32,578
Sam...

104
00:10:33,746 --> 00:10:35,706
I love you!

105
00:10:36,666 --> 00:10:37,583
(softly) I love you!

106
00:10:38,001 --> 00:10:40,211
- And I miss you!
- (softly) I miss you!

107
00:10:41,671 --> 00:10:43,756
And I can't wait to see you.

108
00:10:44,049 --> 00:10:45,424
OK, sweetheart...

109
00:10:46,885 --> 00:10:48,011
Goodbye.

110
00:11:13,871 --> 00:11:14,830
Hi, Doug!

111
00:11:16,165 --> 00:11:18,376
You're really full of yourself,
aren't you, Doug?

112
00:11:19,919 --> 00:11:20,752
Kath...

113
00:11:40,147 --> 00:11:40,982
(tsks) Not good!

114
00:11:41,733 --> 00:11:43,484
[Television]:
What about Dumbo?... (continues)

115
00:12:27,905 --> 00:12:29,157
(groans) Fuck!

116
00:12:29,699 --> 00:12:30,951
God damn it!

117
00:12:31,784 --> 00:12:32,619
Fuck!

118
00:12:35,622 --> 00:12:37,082
Wasn't kind of smart,
was it, Gerty?

119
00:12:38,250 --> 00:12:40,961
- Sam, can I ask how it happened?
- I told you.

120
00:12:41,045 --> 00:12:44,506
I saw something on TV and
I spilled boiling water on my hand.

121
00:12:45,424 --> 00:12:47,300
You saw something on TV?

122
00:12:47,843 --> 00:12:50,011
Yeah, I something on TV
that distracted me.

123
00:12:50,429 --> 00:12:52,098
Is there something
wrong with that, Gerty?

124
00:12:52,431 --> 00:12:55,017
Sam, you said it was the TV
that distracted you...

125
00:12:55,226 --> 00:12:57,729
but when I came in,
the TV wasn't on.

126
00:12:57,853 --> 00:13:00,147
Perhaps you were imagining things?

127
00:13:03,359 --> 00:13:05,152
Yeah, you think too much, pal.

128
00:13:07,656 --> 00:13:10,158
You need to get laid.
I'm going to go back to work.

129
00:13:50,491 --> 00:13:53,953
(Alarm clock blares Chesney Hawkes'
"The One and Only")

130
00:14:05,215 --> 00:14:06,132
Shut up!

131
00:14:39,834 --> 00:14:41,085
Good morning, Gerty.

132
00:14:41,586 --> 00:14:42,420
Good morning, Sam.

133
00:14:42,546 --> 00:14:44,297
- How are you today?
- Fine!

134
00:14:44,839 --> 00:14:45,882
Fine.

135
00:14:46,090 --> 00:14:48,176
- How is the hand?
- Oh, it's a little sore!

136
00:14:48,676 --> 00:14:50,137
A little sore. It's OK.

137
00:14:52,555 --> 00:14:55,892
- What's for breakfast?
- The usual.

138
00:14:55,996 --> 00:14:56,936
Mmhmm.

139
00:15:01,606 --> 00:15:04,526
- Two weeks to go, Sam.
- Two weeks to go, buddy!

140
00:15:05,485 --> 00:15:07,654
Would you like some
hot sauce on your beans?

141
00:15:08,822 --> 00:15:11,200
No, my tummy's a little tender, actually.

142
00:15:13,285 --> 00:15:15,371
But, thank you.
Thank you, Gerty.

143
00:15:15,579 --> 00:15:16,622
You're welcome, Sam.

144
00:15:17,457 --> 00:15:21,418
08:19, Pacific Time.
Readouts are as follows...

145
00:15:21,460 --> 00:15:23,629
Matthew ... 9.8 miles.

146
00:15:25,089 --> 00:15:26,841
Mark is less—

147
00:15:27,384 --> 00:15:28,927
- 9...
- Hey, Gerty!

148
00:15:30,095 --> 00:15:31,429
Rock and roll!

149
00:15:43,525 --> 00:15:44,485
Mark—umm...

150
00:15:45,611 --> 00:15:47,696
Mark is 11 miles on the button.

151
00:15:51,158 --> 00:15:53,034
Luke is a little twitchy today.

152
00:16:06,591 --> 00:16:07,717
Hey, Gerty.

153
00:16:08,676 --> 00:16:11,179
Looks like we have got a
live one out on Matthew.

154
00:16:11,387 --> 00:16:14,807
I'm going to go out in a few minutes.
I'm just going to finish my coffee, OK?

155
00:16:15,642 --> 00:16:16,685
OK, Sam.

156
00:16:22,023 --> 00:16:24,317
[Computer]:
Searching for long-range comms.

157
00:16:27,863 --> 00:16:30,449
Signal failure on long-range comms.

158
00:17:39,478 --> 00:17:42,106
[Computer]:
Danger. Atmosphere compromised.

159
00:18:14,849 --> 00:18:16,308
Where am...

160
00:18:17,142 --> 00:18:20,479
- Where am I?
- Sam, you're in the infirmary.

161
00:18:21,188 --> 00:18:24,317
You had an accident.
Do you remember what happened?

162
00:18:30,156 --> 00:18:33,076
No, I don't...
I don't remember a thing.

163
00:18:35,161 --> 00:18:36,830
Do you remember me?

164
00:18:38,206 --> 00:18:40,500
Yeah, of course I remember you, Gerty.

165
00:18:40,916 --> 00:18:42,876
That's good. That is very good.

166
00:18:43,293 --> 00:18:45,379
It's nice to see you awake again.

167
00:18:45,796 --> 00:18:49,466
I'd like to keep you under observation
here in the infirmary for a few days...

168
00:18:49,675 --> 00:18:51,552
And run some tests.

169
00:18:53,513 --> 00:18:55,097
How long have I been out?

170
00:18:55,598 --> 00:18:58,434
Not long, Sam.
Go back to sleep.

171
00:18:58,643 --> 00:19:01,145
- OK, pal.
- You're still very tired.

172
00:19:01,855 --> 00:19:03,230
We can talk later.

173
00:19:42,313 --> 00:19:43,356
Hello?

174
00:20:07,881 --> 00:20:09,841
(Distant conversation)
[Gerty]: The new Sam is in reworking order.

175
00:20:09,967 --> 00:20:12,970
But we only have two
working harvesters now.

176
00:20:13,178 --> 00:20:14,951
[Overmeyers]: (sarcastically)
Yeah, well,what a surprise!

177
00:20:16,014 --> 00:20:18,934
[Thompson]: Gerty, we're going to have to
find a way to ramp up production.

178
00:20:19,435 --> 00:20:20,394
[Gerty]: I know.

179
00:20:20,603 --> 00:20:23,063
[Overmeyers]: This is incredible!
But how do you manage to destroy...

180
00:20:23,105 --> 00:20:26,860
a fucking rover, a harvester and
an employee all on the same day?

181
00:20:27,067 --> 00:20:29,862
These were extraordinary
circumstances, as you know.

182
00:20:30,196 --> 00:20:32,282
[Thompson]:
Gerty, what is the status on Harvester 3?

183
00:20:32,782 --> 00:20:34,241
How do the repairs look on... (stopped)

184
00:20:34,867 --> 00:20:37,161
- Sam, you're out of bed.
- Yeah.

185
00:20:38,621 --> 00:20:41,332
I wanted to stretch my legs a bit.
Who was that?

186
00:20:44,669 --> 00:20:46,963
We've been having some problems
with the Lunar-Sat...

187
00:20:47,172 --> 00:20:49,174
And our live feed seems to be down.

188
00:20:49,383 --> 00:20:51,885
I was recording a video-message for Central...

189
00:20:52,094 --> 00:20:54,262
Updating them on your progress.

190
00:20:54,679 --> 00:20:56,348
Sam, you need to stay in bed.

191
00:20:56,557 --> 00:20:59,184
You're not ready to walk around yet.

192
00:21:02,730 --> 00:21:04,899
Can you bring me my sunglasses?
It's really bright in here.

193
00:21:06,692 --> 00:21:09,820
Give me some...
Give me all my stuff, you know?

194
00:21:10,946 --> 00:21:12,824
Your belongings are in your quarters, Sam.

195
00:21:13,157 --> 00:21:16,368
- Well, bring them in here.
- Certainly.

196
00:21:28,047 --> 00:21:29,299
Excellent, Sam.

197
00:21:32,135 --> 00:21:35,347
What...When can I get out of here, Gerty?

198
00:21:35,680 --> 00:21:38,600
Sam, you may have suffered
from brain damage in the crash.

199
00:21:38,892 --> 00:21:42,020
This would explain your slight memory
loss and logic impairment.

200
00:21:45,148 --> 00:21:47,442
So what's the diagnosis?
When can I get back to work?

201
00:21:47,568 --> 00:21:50,070
Central has asked me to
slow down the harvesters...

202
00:21:50,153 --> 00:21:53,199
to ensure you have time to
recuperate and get your strength back.

203
00:21:53,407 --> 00:21:54,325
(sarcastically) That's terrific!

204
00:21:55,284 --> 00:21:56,410
That's fantastic!

205
00:21:56,536 --> 00:21:58,704
You can return to the sleeping quarters tomorrow.

206
00:21:59,038 --> 00:22:03,501
But it will still be a few more days before you
can resume anything like a normal work schedule.

207
00:22:04,961 --> 00:22:06,337
Let's try another test.

208
00:22:06,421 --> 00:22:07,589
I don't want to try another test!

209
00:22:08,631 --> 00:22:10,091
Please, Sam.

210
00:22:38,120 --> 00:22:39,288
Hey, Gerty?

211
00:22:43,042 --> 00:22:43,959
Do you know about this?

212
00:22:45,628 --> 00:22:48,464
Matthew has got no velocity readout.
He is completely still.

213
00:22:49,090 --> 00:22:50,341
He must have stalled.

214
00:22:50,425 --> 00:22:51,759
Well, he has obviously stalled.

215
00:22:51,801 --> 00:22:53,052
Don't you think we should tell Central?

216
00:22:53,762 --> 00:22:55,346
Unlock the doors and I'll go fix it.

217
00:22:56,597 --> 00:22:57,849
I will pass on your message.

218
00:23:39,016 --> 00:23:41,811
[Gerty]: Message received from Earth
via Jupiter link.

219
00:23:41,853 --> 00:23:45,273
[Thompson]: Sam, we appreciate the offer,
but you concentrate on feeling better.

220
00:23:46,023 --> 00:23:48,401
[Overmeyers]: Yeah, we don't want
you to take any unnecessary risks.

221
00:23:49,027 --> 00:23:51,112
- You are too important to us.
- You stay put.

222
00:23:51,947 --> 00:23:52,906
[Overmeyers]: That is an order.

223
00:23:53,197 --> 00:23:54,991
[Thompson]: It's an order, Sam...
from Lunar.

224
00:23:55,075 --> 00:23:57,035
[Overmeyers]:
And what we're going to do is send a rescue unit...

225
00:23:57,076 --> 00:23:59,996
to tend to the stalled harvester
and get the base back on its feet.

226
00:24:00,497 --> 00:24:03,333
- (under breath) Fuck is with...? What the fuck?
- I'm sorry, Sam.

227
00:24:03,542 --> 00:24:04,627
- What?
- Sam...

228
00:24:04,668 --> 00:24:07,505
I'm under strict orders not to let you outside.

229
00:24:09,173 --> 00:24:12,801
I don't appreciate that—being treated like a child.
I don't appreciate it.

230
00:24:51,383 --> 00:24:52,426
Gerty!

231
00:24:58,056 --> 00:24:59,100
Gerty!

232
00:24:59,850 --> 00:25:00,893
Gerty, come here!

233
00:25:01,727 --> 00:25:04,313
- What happened?
- I do not know, maybe a meteorite...

234
00:25:04,939 --> 00:25:06,607
There have been no meteorites, Sam.

235
00:25:07,024 --> 00:25:08,609
Micrometeorites, maybe. I do not know.

236
00:25:08,818 --> 00:25:11,112
Either way, there might be
damage to the exterior shell.

237
00:25:11,321 --> 00:25:13,907
I think you better...you better
let me go outside and take a look.

238
00:25:14,032 --> 00:25:16,201
There is no damage to the exterior shell.

239
00:25:16,409 --> 00:25:18,411
Well, it's not that I don't believe you, Gerty...

240
00:25:18,495 --> 00:25:21,539
But, you know, this thing is
springing leaks like an Acme firehose.

241
00:25:21,832 --> 00:25:24,042
You need to let me go outside
and fix this problem, Gery.

242
00:25:24,459 --> 00:25:26,211
I can't let you go outside, Sam.

243
00:25:26,628 --> 00:25:29,464
Gerty, if you don't let me go outside,
we can't fix this leak.

244
00:25:29,548 --> 00:25:31,591
I'm not permitted to let you go outside.

245
00:25:31,633 --> 00:25:34,553
Just let...
We'll keep it between you and me, ok, pal?

246
00:25:35,512 --> 00:25:37,681
This thing is leaking gas. Let's go! Come on...

247
00:25:38,515 --> 00:25:40,622
Just to check the exterior shell?

248
00:25:40,725 --> 00:25:42,477
- Of course.
- OK, Sam.

249
00:25:42,603 --> 00:25:43,645
Thank you.

250
00:25:58,119 --> 00:25:59,078
Gerty!

251
00:26:33,364 --> 00:26:35,033
[Computer]:
Searching for long-range comms.

252
